		<title>FAQ: Whatâs the difference between a tachometer and an encoder?</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/MotionControlTips/~3/vvN-Jh6E4Js/</link>
		<comments>http://www.motioncontroltips.com/faq-whats-difference-tachometer-encoder/#respond</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 17 Jan 2017 19:56:26 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Miles Budimir]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Basics + FAQs]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Encoders]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.motioncontroltips.com/?p=15089</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Basically, the short answer is that a tachometer gives speed information only (i.e. how fast a piece of machinery is rotating) while an encoder gives position information about some piece of machinery (i.e. where it is in s pace at some given time). The information can be about rotary position (as with rotary encoders) or [&#8230;]</p>
<p><a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.motioncontroltips.com">Motion Control Tips</a></p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Basically, the short answer is that a tachometer gives speed information only (i.e. how fast a piece of machinery is rotating) while an encoder gives position information about some piece of machinery (i.e. where it is in s</p>
<div id="attachment_15090" style="width: 270px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="http://www.motioncontroltips.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Novotechnik_encoder.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-15090" src="http://www.motioncontroltips.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Novotechnik_encoder.jpg" alt="encoders" width="260" height="274" srcset="http://3l4sbp4ao2771ln0f54chhvm.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Novotechnik_encoder.jpg 324w, http://3l4sbp4ao2771ln0f54chhvm.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Novotechnik_encoder-285x300.jpg 285w" sizes="(max-width: 260px) 100vw, 260px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Some rotary encoders, such as this model Vert-X 51 from Novotechnik U.S., use magnetic techniques instead of optical ones to measure rotary position.</p></div>
<p>pace at some given time). The information can be about rotary position (as with rotary encoders) or linear position with linear encoders.</p>
<p>Encoders take rotary position and convert it to either an analog or digital signal. Encoders can also take information about position and calculate speed, so in this sense they are more versatile than a simple tachometer. However, modern tachometers arenât only confined to machine-mounted units. Aside from the traditional round, analog display type, a range of companies manufacture hand-held models that use lasers to measure speed of rotating equipment.</p>
<p>So if speed is the only variable of interest, then a simple tachometer will do the job and you wonât be paying more for extra functionality that you donât need.</p>
<div id="attachment_15091" style="width: 560px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="http://www.motioncontroltips.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/SKF_tachometer.png"><img class="size-full wp-image-15091" src="http://www.motioncontroltips.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/SKF_tachometer.png" alt="tachometer " width="550" height="221" srcset="http://3l4sbp4ao2771ln0f54chhvm.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/SKF_tachometer.png 550w, http://3l4sbp4ao2771ln0f54chhvm.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/SKF_tachometer-300x121.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 550px) 100vw, 550px" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Hand-held digital tachometers, pictured from SKF, use either laser or contact techniques to measure rotational or linear speeds.</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
